at ighing by his beautiful Eleanor, and he feated her elf with the weetnes of liberty to enjoy in afety the converation of a Lover he had given over for lot. Aen was buie giving orders in the Brigandine;
but being becalmed on the udden, and no way to be made but by rowing, he ate by them to congratulate their happines. 'Tis true, ays Eleanor, I hould eteem my elf the mot fortunate peron on Earth, if after what you have aur'd me of the Marques, you could eae me of the cruples, the Turks habit he wears, raies within me. Was it poible, adds he bluhing, you hould change your Religion? 'Tis the very thing I longed to know of him, Madam, and how he came to Barbary, for he hath not yet told me. No, Madam, anwers Hippolito, I am till a Chritian, and had I been threatned with Death, or with Torments, I hould not have changed my Religion, but 'tis true I have been long thought a Turk. Aen, who could not conceive how it could be o in a Country like his, where in matters of Religion, there are Formalities not to be counterfeited, pray'd him to declare what coure he had taken, and how it was poible for him to ecape Circumciion, being the firt of the Ceremonies ued in that cae. Hippolito to atisfie him, knowing
he hould at the ame time do Eleanor a pleaure, went on with his tory.
